A: The problem is that you are not writing a line break after each write. When you use PrintWriter.write(), it doesn't automatically add a line break. You need to manually add it.
Here is the corrected code:
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.write("1\n");
printWriter.write("2\n");
printWriter.write("3\n");

The "\n" character is a line break in text files.

A: You are writing each line without a newline character. The BufferedReader.readLine() method reads until it encounters a newline character. If you don't include a newline character, the BufferedReader.readLine() method will only read the first line of your three lines.
You can fix this by adding a newline character after each write:
printWriter.write("1\n");
printWriter.write("2\n");
printWriter.write("3\n");

This tells the BufferedReader to stop reading after each line.

A: You can use BufferedReader.readLine() to read the file line by line. Here is an example:
BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
String line;
while ((line = bufferedReader.readLine()) != null) {
    System.out.println(line);
}
bufferedReader.close();

This will read the file line by line and print each line to the console. It doesn't load the whole file into memory, which is more efficient for large files.

